      Bad mergers
   =20
 =20

As a first approximation, if you are the chief executive officer of a big p=
ublic company, you can do whatever you want. You are the boss, you write th=
e checks, and if you want to spend your company=E2=80=99s money on buying y=
ourself a nicer office chair or upgrading the corporate jet, you can. If yo=
u are the CEO of a ball bearings company and you want to open a film studio=
 so that you can hang out with movie stars, sure, you=E2=80=99re the boss. =
Or if you are the CEO of a payments company and you want to buy Jay-Z=E2=80=
=99s music streaming company because you like hanging out with Jay-Z, you c=
an do that.
This is only a first approximation, of course, and there are=C2=A0constrain=
ts. There are legal constraints: You can=E2=80=99t do crimes, or conceal wh=
at you=E2=80=99re doing from your board, or take bribes. But the main const=
raints are probably something like:
=09You have a board of directors, and they are technically your boss, and t=
hey can fire you if you do too much dumb stuff.=09Some big decisions =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0mergers, for instance =E2=80=94=C2=A0require board approval, so yo=
u can=E2=80=99t even do big dumb stuff unless they sign off first.=09You ha=
ve shareholders, and if you do too much dumb stuff, they might kick you out=
. (In practice this means that an activist shareholder might win a proxy fi=
ght to kick you out, or a hostile acquirer might buy your company to kick y=
ou out.)=09You=C2=A0are a shareholder, and if you do too much dumb stuff yo=
ur shares will lose value and you will be poorer.=09You probably got to whe=
re you are, being the CEO of a public company, by internalizing an ethos of=
 shareholder value maximization, and you probably=C2=A0want=C2=A0to do righ=
t by shareholders. Sure you=E2=80=99ll buy yourself a nice office chair, bu=
t you will make big decisions by asking yourself =E2=80=9Cis this best for =
shareholders,=E2=80=9D and if you don=E2=80=99t have a good answer you won=
=E2=80=99t do it.
  [1]



I suspect that No. 5 is the main constraint for most CEOs, most of the time=
. But it is worth saying that some CEOs are not really subject to some of t=
hese constraints. Some CEOs =E2=80=94=C2=A0particularly charismatic founder=
-CEOs who were=C2=A0not=C2=A0socialized in an ethos of shareholder value =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0might=C2=A0not=C2=A0care about doing right by shareholders. =
They might own a lot of stock, or super-voting stock, in the company, makin=
g activism or hostile takeovers unlikely. And while a lot of their net wort=
h might be tied up in their company, they might be rich and weird enough no=
t to care very much about how their decisions affect their personal wealth.=
=C2=A0
So then the main constraint is the board.
  [2]
=C2=A0If you are the CEO of a payments company and you dial in to a board m=
eeting from your Hamptons vacation with Jay-Z and say =E2=80=9Chey, I=E2=80=
=99m here with Jay-Z, he=E2=80=99s got a music streaming company, I think w=
e should buy it,=E2=80=9D it=E2=80=99s your board=E2=80=99s job to tell you=
 no.=C2=A0But what if they tell you yes?=C2=A0
In fact, Block Inc. (formerly Square Inc.), the payments company run by Jac=
k Dorsey, acquired Tidal, the music streaming company run by Shawn Carter (=
Jay-Z), in April 2021. Dorsey is rich (even outside of his Block shares), o=
wns  super-voting Block stock, and, uh, is not a conventional shareholder-v=
alue-maximizing public-company CEO. Here is an incredible summary of how th=
e deal came about:

Block facilitates payment processing and helps individuals transfer money e=
lectronically; it had never ventured into the music streaming industry and,=
 at the time it acquired TIDAL, had no plans to do so. The idea for the acq=
uisition came to Jack Dorsey=E2=80=94Block=E2=80=99s founder, CEO, and Chai=
rman=E2=80=94when he was summering with Carter in the Hamptons. From his Ha=
mptons retreat, Dorsey joined a videoconference meeting of Block=E2=80=99s =
board and proposed that Block acquire TIDAL. The board formed a transaction=
 committee to consider the proposal.
Over the ensuing months, the committee learned that TIDAL was failing finan=
cially, losing its major contracts, and facing an ongoing criminal investig=
ation. The committee also learned that Carter personally loaned TIDAL $50 m=
illion to help the troubled company through its difficulties and that Dorse=
y was the sole Block management member in support of the acquisition. Despi=
te the obvious problems with the deal, the committee approved the transacti=
on for $306 million. It seemed, by all accounts, a terrible business decisi=
on.

Shareholders sued, and that summary is from=C2=A0the opening of  a Delaware=
 Chancery Court opinion in the case yesterday. The shareholders lost! The o=
pinion goes on:
Under Delaware law, however, a board comprised of a majority of disinterest=
ed and independent directors is free to make a terrible business decision w=
ithout any meaningful threat of liability, so long as the directors approve=
 the action in good faith.
The important point here is that courts in Delaware =E2=80=94=C2=A0where ma=
ny US public companies are incorporated =E2=80=94=C2=A0do not want to be in=
 the business of deciding whether any particular business decision is terri=
ble. So Delaware has a =E2=80=9Cbusiness judgment rule,=E2=80=9D in which c=
ourts try not to second-guess the business judgments of corporate directors=
. This rule is not absolute: The directors have a duty of care and a duty o=
f loyalty to shareholders; if they have a conflict of interest, or if they =
are incredibly lazy and careless, a court might review their decisions and =
hold them liable for breaching their duties. But if they have no conflicts =
of interest and more or less=C2=A0act like directors, and their decisions a=
re terrible, courts won=E2=80=99t do anything about it.
  [3]

Delaware is=C2=A0proud=C2=A0of this rule; this rule is not just =E2=80=9Cwh=
addarya gonna do sometimes boards do bad stuff,=E2=80=9D but a positively g=
ood=C2=A0thing. Letting boards =E2=80=9Cmake a terrible business decision w=
ithout any meaningful threat of liability=E2=80=9D allows companies to take=
 risks, to make business decisions based on their honest assessment of what=
 is best for shareholders rather than on fear of liability.
And so when a Delaware judge =E2=80=94=C2=A0here, Chancellor Kathaleen McCo=
rmick =E2=80=94=C2=A0gets a case like this, and decides that the directors =
should not be liable, she does not write an opinion saying =E2=80=9Cehh thi=
s was all fine, it=E2=80=99s not as bad as you think.=E2=80=9D She writes a=
n opinion saying =E2=80=9Clol this was all ridiculous, but even so I=E2=80=
=99m going to allow it, because around here we defer to independent boards =
of directors.=E2=80=9D
So the opinion is not kind to Block=E2=80=99s directors:
Plaintiff alleges that Dorsey caused Block to submit a letter of intent to =
purchase TIDAL before the Transaction Committee was even formed. The Transa=
ction Committee then allowed Dorsey to handle negotiations. After discussin=
g the opportunity for only thirty-five minutes during their first meeting i=
n September, the Transaction Committee encouraged Dorsey to move forward. I=
n advance of its second meeting in October, management provided a report th=
at showed just how dire TIDAL=E2=80=99s market position looked.
But the standard for liability is high, and shareholders can only sue if th=
e directors approved the deal in bad faith.=C2=A0One way to prove that is w=
ith a conflict of interest. And for=C2=A0Dorsey=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0who is =
the chairman of Block=E2=80=99s board =E2=80=94=C2=A0that seems plausible. =
The conflict of interest is that he spent shareholder money to=C2=A0get to =
hang out with Jay-Z: =E2=80=9CIt is reasonably conceivable that Dorsey used=
 corporate coffers to bolster his relationship with Carter.=E2=80=9D (At Bl=
oomberg Law,   Mike Leonard notes that =E2=80=9Canalysts blasted the deal a=
s =E2=80=98a $300 million bar tab to hang out with Jay-Z,=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D=
 and Block=E2=80=99s stock dropped 7% when it was announced.)
But the=C2=A0other=C2=A0directors voted to approve the deal, and=C2=A0they=
=C2=A0didn=E2=80=99t get to hang out with Jay-Z. Instead the question for t=
hem is whether they =E2=80=9Cconsciously and intentionally disregarded thei=
r responsibilities, adopting a =E2=80=98we don=E2=80=99t care about the ris=
k=E2=80=99 attitude concerning a material corporate decision,=E2=80=9D whet=
her they =E2=80=9Cknew that they were making material decisions without ade=
quate information and without adequate deliberation, and that they simply d=
id not care if the decisions caused the corporation and its stockholders to=
 suffer injury or loss.=E2=80=9D
  [4]
=C2=A0If they approved the deal carefully=C2=A0enough, then the deal is all=
owed, even if the CEO was conflicted in bringing it to them.
And they approved it carefully enough:
Plaintiff does not allege that the Transaction Committee lacked a business =
reason for wanting to acquire TIDAL=E2=80=94the presentation materials show=
 management=E2=80=99s=C2=A0strategic goals for expanding Block into the mus=
ic industry.=C2=A0Plaintiff does not allege that any of the Committee Defen=
dants were in any way beholden to Dorsey. Plaintiff acknowledge that the Co=
mmittee Defendants did not sit idly by while Dorsey presented. They asked m=
any appropriate questions before the October 20 meeting, and they asked man=
y appropriate follow-up questions in advance of the next meeting on January=
 22. The Transaction Committee were presented with over twenty single-space=
d slides providing management=E2=80=99s detailed answers to each of these q=
uestions.
Now, sure, those answers were bad:

As Plaintiff sees it, the problem was not that the Transaction Committee fa=
iled to ask questions=E2=80=94it is that the answers did not seem to matter=
.
Before its October meeting, the Transaction Committee asked whether any oth=
er members of senior management supported the acquisition; in response, the=
 committee learned that there were none, aside from Dorsey. The Transaction=
 Committee asked whether the artist commitments, which formed the basis for=
 at least half of management=E2=80=99s valuation of TIDAL, were legally enf=
orceable; in response, the committee learned that Block would have =E2=80=
=9Cno recourse=E2=80=9D if the artists decided to walk away. The Transactio=
n Committee asked for near- and long-term plans for integrating TIDAL into =
Block=E2=80=99s business; in response, the committee learned that managemen=
t had not created these plans and that this remained =E2=80=9Cone of the bi=
ggest risks.=E2=80=9D
After the October meeting, the Transaction Committee went dark for three mo=
nths while Dorsey negotiated the purchase price. Ultimately, without any fu=
rther meetings, the Transaction Committee approved the acquisition by unani=
mous written consent.

But that=E2=80=99s all fine: =E2=80=9CAlthough the facts emphasized by Plai=
ntiff do not generate tremendous confidence in the Transaction Committee=E2=
=80=99s process, they fall short of supporting an inference of bad faith.=
=E2=80=9D (Also, to be fair, the deal was=C2=A0small =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=
=9CManagement also responded toquestions about the acquisition=E2=80=99s sc=
ale, noting that a $350 million purchase price would only constitute 0.35% =
of Block=E2=80=99s $100 billion market capitalization=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0so it was not unreasonable for the board not to spend=C2=A0too=C2=A0much=
 time on it.) The process=C2=A0was good enough =E2=80=94=C2=A0the board ask=
ed questions and got answers =E2=80=94=C2=A0even if the results were bad. T=
he law can make boards of directors check the right boxes, but=C2=A0it can=
