 =20

One important issue in modern financial markets is settlement time. It used=
 to be that, if you bought a stock from me on a stock exchange, we would me=
et at the exchange and agree on the trade, and then I would go back to my v=
ault and get my stock certificates, while you would go to your bank and sta=
nd in line and fill out a form and get a sack of gold coins to pay me, and =
then we=E2=80=99d meet back up to hand over the certificates and coins, and=
 we traveled between the exchange and the bank and the vault and the meetin=
g place on foot, and we took long lunches, etc., and so all of this took a =
week: We=E2=80=99d agree a trade on Monday, and hand over shares and coins =
the following Monday. Only in the 1990s did US stock markets move to three-=
business-day (=E2=80=9CT+3=E2=80=9D) settlement. Only this year did the Sec=
urities and Exchange Commission=C2=A0finalize rules to move to one-business=
-day (=E2=80=9CT+1=E2=80=9D) settlement; they won=E2=80=99t fully take effe=
ct until=C2=A0May 2024. The US stock market =E2=80=94=C2=A0one of the faste=
st-moving financial markets =E2=80=94=C2=A0still takes two days between agr=
eeing on a trade and actually handing over the money.
People get mad about this delay, but for the most part it is=C2=A0not=C2=A0=
about, like, archaic computer systems. For the most part it is about=C2=A0f=
inancing. If trades settled instantly =E2=80=94=C2=A0if you agreed to buy a=
 stock from me on the stock exchange at 12:02 on a Monday, and then we exch=
anged cash for shares at 12:02:00.001 =E2=80=94=C2=A0then everyone would ne=
ed to=C2=A0pre-fund=C2=A0their accounts. You would need to keep cash somewh=
ere accessible to the exchange at all times, so that as soon as your buy or=
der got filled the money would be there. With T+2 or T+1 settlement, you ca=
n agree to do a trade and=C2=A0then=C2=A0go find the money. Maybe you have =
it invested in Treasury bills to get some yield, and the two-day delay lets=
 you sell the bills to get the cash to buy the stock. Or maybe you need to=
=C2=A0borrow=C2=A0the money, from a bank or prime broker, to fund the trade=
. Big market makers and hedge funds are often levered, and someone else adv=
ances them the money to pay for their trades. It is helpful to have a day o=
r two to line up that borrowing.
Meanwhile in, like, large-capitalization public-company mergers and acquisi=
tions, settlement delays can be measured in months or years.=C2=A0A private=
 equity firm signs a merger agreement to buy a company, and then it has a f=
ew months to go out to the leveraged-loan and junk-bond markets and raise t=
he money it needs to pay for the company.
  [11]
=C2=A0Sometimes things go wrong in the interim, and then there are many law=
suits. It would be better, for the seller, to just get the money instantly,=
 but that is not the norm. One reason it is not the norm is that private eq=
uity firms do not, like, borrow $20 billion in advance just to have it in t=
heir bank account in case they do a deal. It does not make a lot of sense t=
o pre-fund=C2=A0huge=C2=A0investments. First you agree to do a $20 billion =
leveraged buyout,=C2=A0then=C2=A0you go out and get the $20 billion.=C2=A0
The traditional way that venture capital works is that a VC fund raises=C2=
=A0commitments=C2=A0from its limited partners (the institutions and people =
who invest in the fund): When it=C2=A0raises a $1 billion fund, investors d=
o=C2=A0not=C2=A0wire it $1 billion immediately to plop into a bank account.=
 Instead each investor says =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m good for $20 million=E2=80=
=9D or whatever, and they sign an agreement committing them to put in that =
amount, and then the investors keep the money and the VC fund goes out look=
ing for investments. And when it finds one, it issues a capital call, and i=
ts LPs send in some money, and it uses the money to make the investment. An=
d all of this takes a little time: The LPs have to move the money out of wh=
erever=C2=A0they=E2=80=99re=C2=A0keeping it=C2=A0and wire it to the VC firm=
, and the VC firm has to put it all together and send another wire to the p=
ortfolio company in order to pay for the investment.=C2=A0
And in the recent VC boom I guess people got impatient and it became a comp=
etitive advantage for VC firms to say to portfolio companies, like, =E2=80=
=9Cif you sign this termsheet we will wire you the money tomorrow.=E2=80=9D=
 The market demanded shorter settlement times. One way to provide shorter s=
ettlement times would be that VC firms could get all the cash for their fun=
ds upfront and hold onto it until they are ready to invest: The limited par=
tners could put cash into the fund at the beginning,. This seems inefficien=
t, and limited partners wouldn=E2=80=99t like it.
The more standard and appealing way to do it is with borrowing: VC firms ca=
n set up lines of credit with a bank, and when they sign a deal they can ca=
ll the bank and say =E2=80=9Cwe need $100 million to do this deal,=E2=80=9D=
 and the bank=C2=A0sends the money that day, and then a week or two later w=
hen all the LP money comes in, the VC firm pays back the bank.
This sort of thing is called =E2=80=9Ccapital call financing=E2=80=9D or so=
metimes =E2=80=9Csubscription line financing.=E2=80=9D At leveraged buyout =
firms, this sort of product=C2=A0is famously an opportunity for financial g=
amesmanship. (Basically if the buyout=C2=A0firm=C2=A0waits longer=C2=A0to c=
all capital, using the subscription line financing for months or years rath=
er than days or weeks, it can report a higher rate of return on its LPs=E2=
=80=99 money, because it is using that money for less time.) But even witho=
ut the gamesmanship this product can be desirable in venture capital, becau=
se it satisfies (1) startups=E2=80=99 desire to get cash fast and (2) ventu=
re capital limited partners=E2=80=99 desire not to lock up their money befo=
re it is needed. Banks, who have lots of money at all times, grease the whe=
els of VC investing.
But then some VC-friendly banks ran into trouble, which means that this VC-=
friendly banking product is in trouble. At the Information, Michael Roddan =
and Kate Clark report:

In the past, these VC firms relied on a specialized credit line offered by =
SVB and a handful of other banks, including First Republic Bank, that plugg=
ed the gap between when the investors, or limited partners, commit capital =
to VC funds and when that cash actually arrives. But the collapse of both S=
VB and First Republic is expected to make these loans harder to get. Big ba=
nks=E2=80=94such as JPMorgan Chase, which took over First Republic=E2=80=99=
s business=E2=80=94are wary of extending these loans, known as capital call=
 credit lines, to the small VC firms that need them most but are seen as ri=
skier bets. ...
Unless some banks step in to offer the credit lines, small VC firms may hav=
e less ability to move quickly on startup investments, making it harder for=
 them to compete with large firms.
=E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s going to become more and more difficult for smaller V=
C funds,=E2=80=9D said Dolph Hellman, a partner in San Francisco with Orric=
k Herrington & Sutcliffe who advises startups and private investors on capi=
tal call credit lines. =E2=80=A6
The risk for the banks is that the investor will renege on their commitment=
, which means the VC firm won=E2=80=99t be able to repay the credit line. A=
s a result, before a bank lends money to a small VC fund, it may want to kn=
ow who its LPs are, the fund=E2=80=99s track record and how likely it is to=
 be able to convince investors to make good on the capital call. All that w=
ork increases the time and cost of dealing with small VC funds, which don=
=E2=80=99t provide big lenders with a lot of bang for their buck.
=E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s tougher for the banks to get their arms around who th=
e investors in VC funds are. You=E2=80=99re relying on the fact that the LP=
s are going to honor capital calls. It=E2=80=99s difficult for the banks to=
 determine the creditworthiness of individual investors or family offices,=
=E2=80=9D Hellman said.

One possibility is that, in a weaker environment for startup investing and =
venture capital generally, startups will be willing to wait a few weeks to =
get their VC money?

