can vote to have the company sue her. But if *all* of the directors are bre=
aching their fiduciary duties, then obviously they won=E2=80=99t vote to su=
e themselves. And so the law allows shareholders to bring =E2=80=9Cderivati=
ve suits=E2=80=9D on behalf of the company, but only if they can show that =
the company wouldn=E2=80=99t bring the lawsuit itself because the directors=
 are too conflicted. This requirement is called, for somehow even more bori=
ng reasons, =E2=80=9Cdemand futility,=E2=80=9D and it =E2=80=9Chinges on wh=
ether the plaintiff adequately alleges that the [board] members would face =
a substantial likelihood of liability for approving the transaction.=E2=80=
=9D (Another technicality has to do with the exculpatory provisions in the =
company=E2=80=99s charter: =E2=80=9CWhere, as here, the corporation=E2=80=
=99s certificate of incorporation exculpates its directors from liability t=
o the fullest extent permitted by law, the substantial-likelihood standard =
requires that a plaintiff =E2=80=98plead particularized facts providing a r=
eason to believe that the individual director was self-interested, beholden=
 to an interested party, or acted in bad faith.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D)


  [4] These quotes are me quoting Chancellor McCormick quoting a 2006 Chanc=
ery Court decision, In re The Walt Disney Co. Derivative Litigation.


  [5] Incidentally, I=20
write a lot around here about how =E2=80=9Ceverything is securities fraud=
=E2=80=9D: Every bad thing that happens to a public company can be characte=
rized as securities fraud, because shareholders bought the stock thinking t=
hat the bad thing wouldn=E2=80=99t happen, so they can claim they were dece=
ived by the company=E2=80=99s disclosures. If the Delaware rule is, kind of=
, =E2=80=9Cnothing is a breach of fiduciary duties,=E2=80=9D then surely th=
e right move for shareholder lawsuits is to sue for securities fraud instea=
d? =E2=80=9CYou didn=E2=80=99t disclose in your risk factors that Jack Dors=
ey was hanging out with Jay-Z, so  your stock was overvalued,=E2=80=9D etc.


  [6] To be clear the *reason* to be conservative is that you are going to =
have absurdly good earnings this quarter, so they sort of don=E2=80=99t mat=
ter: First Citizens reported net income of $271 million in the first quarte=
r of 2022, $257 million in the fourth quarter  of 2022, and $9.52 billion i=
n the first quarter of 2023, almost all of which was gain on acquisition. (=
=E2=80=9CAdjusted net income available to common shareholders,=E2=80=9D ign=
oring the gain on acquisition, was a more sensible $292 million.) Nobody is=
 updating their financial model to assume that First Citizens will have $9.=
52 billion of quarterly income from now on; that number is sort of meaningl=
ess. But if you mark the assets very conservatively now, and they end up be=
ing worth more than your marks, your meaningless one-time income is lower t=
oday, but you have positive income in *future* quarters, when you want it. =
If you mark the assets pretty high now, and they end up being worth less la=
ter, then your meaningless one-time income is higher today but your future =
earnings are lower. Earnings from SVB=E2=80=99s assets in future quarters a=
re worth way, way, way more to First Citizens than earnings from those asse=
ts today. Counterbalancing this incentive is that, like, your accounting ha=
s to be correct, you have third-party experts reviewing it, etc. But the in=
centives are to mark stuff down.


  [7] Slide 19 of the earnings presentation walks through the math: A $16.4=
5 billion discount on the assets, minus about $2.8 billion of adjustments t=
o the asset values, minus a $500 million cash payment to the FDIC, gets you=
 to $13.1 billion of actual gains. Subtract $3.3 billion of deferred tax li=
ability and you get $9.8 billion.


  [8] The lower number here comes largely from loan loss provisions on the =
SVB assets that do not get counted in the gain-on-acquisition math.


  [9] Again, see slide 19 of the presentation: $110.1 billion of assets min=
us $2.8 billion of adjustments gets you about $107.3 billion of assets at f=
air values. And the price was $93.6 billion of assumed deposits, plus $500 =
million of top-up payment to the FDIC, or $94.1 billion total. This is a li=
ttle casual, and in fact some of the purchase price adjustments are not str=
ictly about the fair value of SVB=E2=80=99s *assets*. For instance there=E2=
=80=99s a $230 million benefit for the =E2=80=9Ccore deposit intangible,=E2=
=80=9D that is, sort of, the deposit franchise. And First Citizens takes a =
$220 million benefit from =E2=80=9Cdiscount on purchase money note=E2=80=9D=
: Part of the assumed liabilities was a $35 billion loan from the FDIC to F=
irst Citizens to provide long-term funding for some of the SVB loans, and t=
hat loan was at below-market rates, creating an additional benefit for Firs=
t Citizens.=20


  [10] See page 6 of the earnings release.


  [11] I=E2=80=99m being a bit cute; most of the delay here is caused by th=
e need to get regulatory approvals and a shareholder vote. If those were in=
stantaneous, you=E2=80=99d probably see the financing markets adapt by gett=
ing quicker.


