<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Bad mergers</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As a first approximation, if you are the chief=
 executive officer of a big public company, you can do whatever you want. Y=
ou are the boss, you write the checks, and if you want to spend your compan=
y=E2=80=99s money on buying yourself a nicer office chair or upgrading the =
corporate jet, you can. If you are the CEO of a ball bearings company and y=
ou want to open a film studio so that you can hang out with movie stars, su=
re, you=E2=80=99re the boss. Or if you are the CEO of a payments company an=
d you want to buy Jay-Z=E2=80=99s music streaming company because you like =
hanging out with Jay-Z, you can do that.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is only a first approximation, of course,=
 and there are=C2=A0constraints. There are legal constraints: You can=E2=80=
=99t do crimes, or conceal what you=E2=80=99re doing from your board, or ta=
ke bribes. But the main constraints are probably something like:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You have a board of directors, and th=
ey are technically your boss, and they can fire you if you do too much dumb=
 stuff.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Some big decisions =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0mergers, for instance =E2=80=94=C2=A0require board approval, so yo=
u can=E2=80=99t even do big dumb stuff unless they sign off first.</li>=09<=
li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You have shareholders, and if you do too m=
uch dumb stuff, they might kick you out. (<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloo=
mbergbusiness.com/click/31439676.262437/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9=
vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDUtMjcvZXh4b24tbG9zdC1hLWNsaW1hdGUtcHJveHktZm=
lnaHQ_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDUxMDIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291c=
mNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwNTEwJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607=
f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7e16d6af" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsco=
pe" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">In practice</a> this means that an =
activist shareholder might win a proxy fight to kick you out, or a hostile =
acquirer might buy your company to kick you out.)</li>=09<li style=3D"margi=
n-bottom: 5px;">You=C2=A0<em>are </em>a shareholder, and if you do too much=
 dumb stuff your shares will lose value and you will be poorer.</li>=09<li =
style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You probably got to where you are, being the =
CEO of a public company, by internalizing an ethos of shareholder value max=
imization, and you probably=C2=A0<em>want=C2=A0</em>to do right by sharehol=
ders. Sure you=E2=80=99ll buy yourself a nice office chair, but you will ma=
ke big decisions by asking yourself =E2=80=9Cis this best for shareholders,=
=E2=80=9D and if you don=E2=80=99t have a good answer you won=E2=80=99t do =
it.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: tr=
ansparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>
</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I suspect that No. 5 is the main constraint fo=
r most CEOs, most of the time. But it is worth saying that some CEOs are no=
t really subject to some of these constraints. Some CEOs =E2=80=94=C2=A0par=
ticularly charismatic founder-CEOs who were=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>socializ=
ed in an ethos of shareholder value =E2=80=94=C2=A0might=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0=
</em>care about doing right by shareholders. They might own a lot of stock,=
 or super-voting stock, in the company, making activism or hostile takeover=
s unlikely. And while a lot of their net worth might be tied up in their co=
mpany, they might be rich and weird enough not to care very much about how =
their decisions affect their personal wealth.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So then the main constraint is the board.<a cl=
ass=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparen=
t !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0If you are the CEO of a payments company and you dial in to a boa=
rd meeting from your Hamptons vacation with Jay-Z and say =E2=80=9Chey, I=
=E2=80=99m here with Jay-Z, he=E2=80=99s got a music streaming company, I t=
hink we should buy it,=E2=80=9D it=E2=80=99s your board=E2=80=99s job to te=
ll you no.=C2=A0But what if they tell you yes?=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In fact, Block Inc. (<a href=3D"https://link.m=
ail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31439676.262437/aHR0cHM6Ly9zcXVhcmV1cC5jb20=
vdXMvZW4vcHJlc3Mvc3F1YXJlLWNoYW5nZXMtbmFtZS10by1ibG9jaw/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
9a23cB3b71c2da" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_b=
lank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;">formerly Square Inc.</a>), the payments company run=
 by Jack Dorsey, acquired Tidal, the music streaming company run by Shawn C=
arter (Jay-Z), in April 2021. Dorsey is rich (even outside of his Block sha=
res), owns <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3143967=
6.262437/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9peD9kb2M9L0FyY2hpdmVzL2VkZ2FyL2RhdGEvMD=
AwMTUxMjY3My8wMDAwOTUwMTcwMjMwMTU3ODgvc3EtMjAyMzA0MjguaHRtI3NlY3VyaXR5X293b=
mVyc2hpcF9vZl9jZXJ0YWluX2JlbmVmaWNpYWw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBdfc85562" i=
temprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: =
#ccc;"> super-voting Block stock</a>, and, uh, <a href=3D"https://link.mail=
.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31439676.262437/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYnVzaW5lc3Npbn=
NpZGVyLmNvbS9mYWJ1bG91cy1saWZlLW9mLWJpbGxpb25haXJlLWphY2stZG9yc2V5LXRha2luZ=
y1zcXVhcmUtcHVibGlj/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4771e440" itemprop=3D"StoryLin=
k" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-=
decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color:=
 #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">is not a con=
ventional shareholder-value-maximizing public-company CEO</a>. Here is an i=
ncredible summary of how the deal came about:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Block facilitates payment processing and helps=
 individuals transfer money electronically; it had never ventured into the =
music streaming industry and, at the time it acquired TIDAL, had no plans t=
o do so. The idea for the acquisition came to Jack Dorsey=E2=80=94Block=E2=
=80=99s founder, CEO, and Chairman=E2=80=94when he was summering with Carte=
r in the Hamptons. From his Hamptons retreat, Dorsey joined a videoconferen=
ce meeting of Block=E2=80=99s board and proposed that Block acquire TIDAL. =
The board formed a transaction committee to consider the proposal.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Over the ensuing months, the committee learned=
 that TIDAL was failing financially, losing its major contracts, and facing=
 an ongoing criminal investigation. The committee also learned that Carter =
personally loaned TIDAL $50 million to help the troubled company through it=
s difficulties and that Dorsey was the sole Block management member in supp=
ort of the acquisition. Despite the obvious problems with the deal, the com=
mittee approved the transaction for $306 million. It seemed, by all account=
s, a terrible business decision.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Shareholders sued, and that summary is from=C2=
=A0the opening of <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/=
31439676.262437/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMuYndieC5pby9kb2N1bWVudHMvdXNlcnMvaXFqV0h=
CRmRmeElVL3IuVGhuMkV3WF9pWS92MA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB50a8c309" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
 a Delaware Chancery Court opinion</a> in the case yesterday. The sharehold=
ers lost! The opinion goes on:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Under Delaware law, however, a boa=
rd comprised of a majority of disinterested and independent directors is fr=
ee to make a terrible business decision without any meaningful threat of li=
ability, so long as the directors approve the action in good faith.</p></bl=
ockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The important point here is that courts in Del=
aware =E2=80=94=C2=A0where many US public companies are incorporated =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0do not want to be in the business of deciding whether any particul=
ar business decision is terrible. So Delaware has a =E2=80=9Cbusiness judgm=
ent rule,=E2=80=9D in which courts try not to second-guess the business jud=
gments of corporate directors. This rule is not absolute: The directors hav=
e a duty of care and a duty of loyalty to shareholders; if they have a conf=
lict of interest, or if they are incredibly lazy and careless, a court migh=
t review their decisions and hold them liable for breaching their duties. B=
ut if they have no conflicts of interest and more or less=C2=A0<em>act like=
 directors</em>, and their decisions are terrible, courts won=E2=80=99t do =
anything about it.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D=
"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px=
; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backg=
round-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Delaware is=C2=A0<em>proud=C2=A0</em>of this r=
ule; this rule is not just =E2=80=9Cwhaddarya gonna do sometimes boards do =
bad stuff,=E2=80=9D but a positively <em>good=C2=A0</em>thing. Letting boar=
ds =E2=80=9Cmake a terrible business decision without any meaningful threat=
 of liability=E2=80=9D allows companies to take risks, to make business dec=
isions based on their honest assessment of what is best for shareholders ra=
ther than on fear of liability.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so when a Delaware judge =E2=80=94=C2=A0he=
re, Chancellor Kathaleen McCormick =E2=80=94=C2=A0gets a case like this, an=
d decides that the directors should not be liable, she does not write an op=
inion saying =E2=80=9Cehh this was all fine, it=E2=80=99s not as bad as you=
 think.=E2=80=9D She writes an opinion saying =E2=80=9Clol this was all rid=
iculous, but even so I=E2=80=99m going to allow it, because around here we =
defer to independent boards of directors.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So the opinion is not kind to Block=E2=80=99s =
directors:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Plaintiff alleges that Dorsey caus=
ed Block to submit a letter of intent to purchase TIDAL before the Transact=
ion Committee was even formed. The Transaction Committee then allowed Dorse=
y to handle negotiations. After discussing the opportunity for only thirty-=
five minutes during their first meeting in September, the Transaction Commi=
ttee encouraged Dorsey to move forward. In advance of its second meeting in=
 October, management provided a report that showed just how dire TIDAL=E2=
=80=99s market position looked.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the standard for liability is high, and sh=
areholders can only sue if the directors approved the deal in bad faith.=C2=
=A0One way to prove that is with a conflict of interest. And for=C2=A0<em>D=
orsey=C2=A0</em>=E2=80=94=C2=A0who is the chairman of Block=E2=80=99s board=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0that seems plausible. The conflict of interest is that he s=
pent shareholder money to=C2=A0get to hang out with Jay-Z: =E2=80=9CIt is r=
easonably conceivable that Dorsey used corporate coffers to bolster his rel=
ationship with Carter.=E2=80=9D (At Bloomberg Law, <a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31439676.262437/aHR0cHM6Ly9uZXdzLmJsb29tYm=
VyZ2xhdy5jb20vZXNnL2phY2stZG9yc2V5LWJsb2NrLWluYy1ib2FyZC1iZWF0LWludmVzdG9yL=
XN1aXQtb3Zlci1qYXktei1kZWFs/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd17e9e5d" itemprop=3D"=
StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  Mi=
ke Leonard notes</a> that =E2=80=9Canalysts blasted the deal as =E2=80=98a =
$300 million bar tab to hang out with Jay-Z,=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D and Block=E2=
=80=99s stock dropped 7% when it was announced.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the=C2=A0<em>other=C2=A0</em>directors vot=
ed to approve the deal, and=C2=A0<em>they=C2=A0</em>didn=E2=80=99t get to h=
ang out with Jay-Z. Instead the question for them is whether they =E2=80=9C=
consciously and intentionally disregarded their responsibilities, adopting =
a =E2=80=98we don=E2=80=99t care about the risk=E2=80=99 attitude concernin=
g a material corporate decision,=E2=80=9D whether they =E2=80=9Cknew that t=
hey were making material decisions without adequate information and without=
 adequate deliberation, and that they simply did not care if the decisions =
caused the corporation and its stockholders to suffer injury or loss.=E2=80=
=9D<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: tr=
ansparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>=C2=A0If they approved the deal carefully=C2=A0<em>enough</em>, then th=
e deal is allowed, even if the CEO was conflicted in bringing it to them.</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And they approved it carefully enough:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Plaintiff does not allege that the=
 Transaction Committee lacked a business reason for wanting to acquire TIDA=
L=E2=80=94the presentation materials show management=E2=80=99s=C2=A0strateg=
ic goals for expanding Block into the music industry.=C2=A0Plaintiff does n=
ot allege that any of the Committee Defendants were in any way beholden to =
Dorsey. Plaintiff acknowledge that the Committee Defendants did not sit idl=
y by while Dorsey presented. They asked many appropriate questions before t=
he October 20 meeting, and they asked many appropriate follow-up questions =
in advance of the next meeting on January 22. The Transaction Committee wer=
e presented with over twenty single-spaced slides providing management=E2=
=80=99s detailed answers to each of these questions.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now, sure, those answers were bad:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As Plaintiff sees it, the problem was not that=
 the Transaction Committee failed to ask questions=E2=80=94it is that the a=
nswers did not seem to matter.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Before its October meeting, the Transaction Co=
mmittee asked whether any other members of senior management supported the =
acquisition; in response, the committee learned that there were none, aside=
 from Dorsey. The Transaction Committee asked whether the artist commitment=
s, which formed the basis for at least half of management=E2=80=99s valuati=
on of TIDAL, were legally enforceable; in response, the committee learned t=
hat Block would have =E2=80=9Cno recourse=E2=80=9D if the artists decided t=
o walk away. The Transaction Committee asked for near- and long-term plans =
for integrating TIDAL into Block=E2=80=99s business; in response, the commi=
ttee learned that management had not created these plans and that this rema=
ined =E2=80=9Cone of the biggest risks.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">After the October meeting, the Transaction Com=
mittee went dark for three months while Dorsey negotiated the purchase pric=
e. Ultimately, without any further meetings, the Transaction Committee appr=
oved the acquisition by unanimous written consent.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But that=E2=80=99s all fine: =E2=80=9CAlthough=
 the facts emphasized by Plaintiff do not generate tremendous confidence in=
 the Transaction Committee=E2=80=99s process, they fall short of supporting=
 an inference of bad faith.=E2=80=9D (Also, to be fair, the deal was=C2=A0<=
em>small</em> =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9CManagement also responded to<br />que=
stions about the acquisition=E2=80=99s scale, noting that a $350 million pu=
rchase price would only constitute 0.35% of Block=E2=80=99s $100 billion ma=
rket capitalization=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0so it was not unreasonable for =
the board not to spend=C2=A0<em>too=C2=A0</em>much time on it.) The <em>pro=
cess</em>=C2=A0was good enough =E2=80=94=C2=A0the board asked questions and=
 got answers =E2=80=94=C2=A0even if the results were bad. The law can make =
boards of directors check the right boxes, but=C2=A0it can=E2=80=99t make t=
hem make the right decisions, and it doesn=E2=80=99t try.<a class=3D"footno=
te-index" href=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: no=
ne !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bord=
er-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important;=
 display: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a></p>
