<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One important issue in modern financial market=
s is settlement time. It used to be that, if you bought a stock from me on =
a stock exchange, we would meet at the exchange and agree on the trade, and=
 then I would go back to my vault and get my stock certificates, while you =
would go to your bank and stand in line and fill out a form and get a sack =
of gold coins to pay me, and then we=E2=80=99d meet back up to hand over th=
e certificates and coins, and we traveled between the exchange and the bank=
 and the vault and the meeting place on foot, and we took long lunches, etc=
., and so all of this took a week: We=E2=80=99d agree a trade on Monday, an=
d hand over shares and coins the following Monday. Only in the 1990s did US=
 stock markets <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/314=
39676.262437/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9hYm91dC9yZXBvcnRzLXB1YmxpY2F0aW9ucy=
9pbnZlc3Rvci1wdWJsaWNhdGlvbnMvYWJvdXQtc2V0dGxpbmctdHJhZGVzLWluLXRocmVlLWRhe=
XMtaW50cm9kdWNpbmctdC0z/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9f293750" itemprop=3D"Stor=
yLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">move to =
three-business-day (=E2=80=9CT+3=E2=80=9D) settlement</a>. Only this year d=
id <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31439676.262437=
/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAyMy0yOQ/607f07ceef4=
b8524a319a23cBbd1d65c5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targ=
et=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bo=
rder-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: =
solid; background-color: #ccc;">the Securities and Exchange Commission=C2=
=A0finalize rules</a> to move to one-business-day (=E2=80=9CT+1=E2=80=9D) s=
ettlement; they won=E2=80=99t fully take effect until=C2=A0May 2024. The US=
 stock market =E2=80=94=C2=A0one of the fastest-moving financial markets =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0still takes two days between agreeing on a trade and actuall=
y handing over the money.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">People get mad about this delay, but for the m=
ost part it is=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>about, like, archaic computer systems=
. For the most part it is about=C2=A0<em>financing</em>. If trades settled =
instantly =E2=80=94=C2=A0if you agreed to buy a stock from me on the stock =
exchange at 12:02 on a Monday, and then we exchanged cash for shares at 12:=
02:00.001 =E2=80=94=C2=A0then everyone would need to=C2=A0<em>pre-fund=C2=
=A0</em>their accounts. You would need to keep cash somewhere accessible to=
 the exchange at all times, so that as soon as your buy order got filled th=
e money would be there. With T+2 or T+1 settlement, you can agree to do a t=
rade and=C2=A0<em>then=C2=A0</em>go find the money. Maybe you have it inves=
ted in Treasury bills to get some yield, and the two-day delay lets you sel=
l the bills to get the cash to buy the stock. Or maybe you need to=C2=A0<em=
>borrow=C2=A0</em>the money, from a bank or prime broker, to fund the trade=
. Big market makers and hedge funds are often levered, and someone else adv=
ances them the money to pay for their trades. It is helpful to have a day o=
r two to line up that borrowing.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile in, like, large-capitalization publi=
c-company mergers and acquisitions, settlement delays can be measured in mo=
nths or years.=C2=A0A private equity firm signs a merger agreement to buy a=
 company, and then it has a few months to go out to the leveraged-loan and =
junk-bond markets and raise the money it needs to pay for the company.<a cl=
ass=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-11" style=3D"color: #000000; text-=
decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color:=
 #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transpare=
nt !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[11]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Sometimes things go wrong in the interim, and then there are many=
 lawsuits. It would be better, for the seller, to just get the money instan=
tly, but that is not the norm. One reason it is not the norm is that privat=
e equity firms do not, like, borrow $20 billion in advance just to have it =
in their bank account in case they do a deal. It does not make a lot of sen=
se to pre-fund=C2=A0<em>huge=C2=A0</em>investments. First you agree to do a=
 $20 billion leveraged buyout,=C2=A0<em>then=C2=A0</em>you go out and get t=
he $20 billion.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The traditional way that venture capital works=
 is that a VC fund raises=C2=A0<em>commitments=C2=A0</em>from its limited p=
artners (the institutions and people who invest in the fund): When it=C2=A0=
raises a $1 billion fund, investors do=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>wire it $1 bi=
llion immediately to plop into a bank account. Instead each investor says =
=E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m good for $20 million=E2=80=9D or whatever, and they si=
gn an agreement committing them to put in that amount, and then the investo=
rs keep the money and the VC fund goes out looking for investments. And whe=
n it finds one, it issues a capital call, and its LPs send in some money, a=
nd it uses the money to make the investment. And all of this takes a little=
 time: The LPs have to move the money out of wherever=C2=A0they=E2=80=99re=
=C2=A0keeping it=C2=A0and wire it to the VC firm, and the VC firm has to pu=
t it all together and send another wire to the portfolio company in order t=
o pay for the investment.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And in the recent VC boom I guess people got i=
mpatient and it became a competitive advantage for VC firms to say to portf=
olio companies, like, =E2=80=9Cif you sign this termsheet we will wire you =
the money tomorrow.=E2=80=9D The market demanded shorter settlement times. =
One way to provide shorter settlement times would be that VC firms could ge=
t all the cash for their funds upfront and hold onto it until they are read=
y to invest: The limited partners could put cash into the fund at the begin=
ning,. This seems inefficient, and limited partners wouldn=E2=80=99t like i=
t.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The more standard and appealing way to do it i=
s with borrowing: VC firms can set up lines of credit with a bank, and when=
 they sign a deal they can call the bank and say =E2=80=9Cwe need $100 mill=
ion to do this deal,=E2=80=9D and the bank=C2=A0sends the money that day, a=
nd then a week or two later when all the LP money comes in, the VC firm pay=
s back the bank.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This sort of thing is called =E2=80=9Ccapital =
call financing=E2=80=9D or sometimes =E2=80=9Csubscription line financing.=
=E2=80=9D At leveraged buyout firms, this sort of product=C2=A0is famously =
<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31439676.262437/aH=
R0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDQtMTgvcHVyc=
GxlLWR1bXBzLWl0cy1wcnBscz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNTEwMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVt=
PWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA1MTAmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWd=
